If you don&#39;t want to write many different constructors, even if this is the cleanest solution from my perspective, because you can define which combinations of parameters are valid, there are several possibilities to deal with it.

 1. Use optional parameters, that can reduce the number of necessary constructors, e.g.:

        public FtpProvider(string serverUri, string user = null, string password = null, bool useSSL = false, bool usePassive = false)
        {
        //stuff
        }

 2. Expose the parameters as public fields, then you can do the following to initialize the object:

        var remoteFileOperator = new FtpProvider(ftpUri)
        {
            user = &quot;user1&quot;,
            password = &quot;12345&quot;
        };

 3. There are other solutions like a fluent builder pattern, that can be nice to use, but require a lot more implementation...

